🎯 Java Constructors – Complete Notes (Student Friendly)
🏗️ What is a Constructor?

A Constructor is a special member of a class that is automatically executed when an object is created.

👉 Its main purpose is to initialize object data (instance variables).

🔹 Syntax
class Student {

    Student() {
        System.out.println("Constructor Called");
    }
}
🔹 Example
class Student {
    int id;
    String name;

    Student(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }
}

Student s1 = new Student(101, "Vikas");
🧠 Memory Trick
Object Creation ➜ Constructor Call ➜ Object Initialization
🤔 Why Do We Need Constructors?

Imagine you are admitting students into a college.

Without Constructor:

Student s = new Student();

s.id = 101;
s.name = "Vikas";

You must manually fill every detail.

With Constructor:

Student s = new Student(101, "Vikas");

Everything is initialized immediately.

✅ Benefits

✔ Automatic initialization

✔ Less code

✔ Better readability

✔ Avoids uninitialized objects

✔ Ensures valid object creation

