⭐ Characteristics of Constructors
1️⃣ Constructor Name = Class Name

✅ Correct

class Student {

    Student() {
    }
}

❌ Wrong

class Student {

    void student() {
    }
}
2️⃣ No Return Type

❌ Wrong

void Student() {
}

❌ Wrong

int Student() {
    return 0;
}

✅ Correct

Student() {
}
3️⃣ Called Automatically
Student s = new Student();

Java automatically calls the constructor.

No manual call needed.

4️⃣ Runs Once Per Object
Student s1 = new Student();
Student s2 = new Student();

Output:

Constructor
Constructor

Because two objects are created.

📚 Types of Constructors
1️⃣ Default Constructor

No parameters.

class Student {

    Student() {
        System.out.println("Default Constructor");
    }
}
Output
Default Constructor
Use Case

When no initial values are required.

2️⃣ Parameterized Constructor

Accepts values.

class Student {

    int id;
    String name;

    Student(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }
}
Object Creation
Student s = new Student(101, "Vikas");
Use Case

When object data is known during creation.

3️⃣ Copy Constructor (User Defined)

Creates a copy of another object.

class Student {

    int id;
    String name;

    Student(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }

    Student(Student s) {
        this.id = s.id;
        this.name = s.name;
    }
}
Student s1 = new Student(101, "Vikas");
Student s2 = new Student(s1);
Use Case

Duplicate an existing object.

🤖 Compiler-Generated Default Constructor

If you don't create any constructor:

class Student {
    int id;
}

Java automatically creates:

Student() {
}
Important Rule

⚠️ If you write even one constructor, Java will NOT generate the default constructor.

🔄 Constructor Overloading

Same constructor name with different parameters.

class Student {

    Student() {
    }

    Student(int id) {
    }

    Student(int id, String name) {
    }
}
Object Creation
Student s1 = new Student();

Student s2 = new Student(101);

Student s3 = new Student(101, "Vikas");
🎯 this Keyword

this refers to the current object.

class Student {

    int id;

    Student(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }
}
Why this?

Without this:

id = id;

Java gets confused between parameter and instance variable.

With this:

this.id = id;

Clearly refers to the instance variable.

⛓️ Constructor Chaining

One constructor calls another constructor.

class Student {

    Student() {
        this(101);
        System.out.println("Default");
    }

    Student(int id) {
        System.out.println(id);
    }
}
Output
101
Default
Rules

✅ Must be first statement

✅ Used within same class

👨‍👦 Calling Parent Constructor

Using super().

class Person {

    Person() {
        System.out.println("Person Constructor");
    }
}

class Student extends Person {

    Student() {
        super();
        System.out.println("Student Constructor");
    }
}
Output
Person Constructor
Student Constructor
⚔️ Constructor vs Method
Feature	             Constructor 🏗️	          Method ⚙️
Name	             Same as class           	Any name
Return                  TypeNo                	Yes/No
Called	             Automatically	             Manually
Purpose	          Initialize object	             Perform task
Execution	During creation	                   When called
Example
class Student {

    Student() {
        System.out.println("Constructor");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Method");
    }
}

Output:

Constructor
Method
🚫 Constructor Restrictions
Can Constructor be Static?

❌ No

static Student() {
}

Not allowed.

Can Constructor be Final?

❌ No

final Student() {
}

Not allowed.

Can Constructor be Abstract?

❌ No

Constructors must have a body.

Can Constructor be Private?

✅ Yes

private Student() {
}

Used in Singleton Design Pattern.

🎤 Interview Questions
Q1. Can Constructors Be Overloaded?

✅ Yes

Student() {}

Student(int id) {}

Student(int id, String name) {}
Q2. Can Constructors Be Overridden?

❌ No

Because constructors are not inherited.

Q3. What is the First Statement in a Constructor?

Either:

this()

or

super()
Q4. What Happens if We Don't Create Any Constructor?

Java creates a default constructor automatically.

Q5. Can a Constructor Return a Value?

❌ No

Constructors never have a return type.

